  "answer": "## Answer\nWithout fine-tuning, self-improving agents usually improve **at test time** by changing prompts, memory, search state, or tool-use behavior rather than model weights. The main families of techniques are: **reflection/memory**, **iterative self-feedback and revision**, **reasoning+acting with external tools**, **search over multiple reasoning branches**, **self-consistency over sampled solutions**, and **curriculum/skill-library accumulation**. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366?utm_source=openai))\n\n- **Reflection + episodic memory:** the agent critiques its own past behavior, stores the reflection, and reuses it on later attempts. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366?utm_source=openai))\n- **Iterative self-feedback / rewrite:** the same model generates an answer, critiques it, and revises it in a loop, with no extra training. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.17651?utm_source=openai))\n- **Reasoning + acting:** the agent alternates between internal reasoning and external actions (APIs, environments, tools) to gather new information and update plans. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629?utm_source=openai))\n- **Search / backtracking over thoughts:** the agent branches over candidate reasoning steps, evaluates them, and can backtrack when a branch looks weak. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.10601?utm_source=openai))\n- **Self-consistency:** the agent samples multiple reasoning paths and selects the most consistent final answer. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2203.11171?utm_source=openai))\n- **Curriculum + skill library:** the agent accumulates reusable skills and follows an automatic curriculum, improving via black-box prompting rather than fine-tuning. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.16291?utm_source=openai))\n\n## Sources\n- Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning — https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366 ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366?utm_source=openai))\n- Self-Refine: Iterative Refinement with Self-Feedback — https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.17651 ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.17651?utm_source=openai))\n- ReAct: Synergizing Reasoning and Acting in Language Models — https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629 ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629?utm_source=openai))\n- Tree of Thoughts: Deliberate Problem Solving with Large Language Models — https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.10601 ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.10601?utm_source=openai))\n- Self-Consistency Improves Chain of Thought Reasoning in Language Models — https://arxiv.org/abs/2203.11171 ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2203.11171?utm_source=openai))\n- Voyager: An Open-Ended Embodied Agent with Large Language Models — https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.16291 ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.16291?utm_source=openai))\n\n## Limitations\nThis is a synthesis from a small set of primary LLM-agent papers, so it is not an exhaustive taxonomy. The papers use different terms for overlapping ideas, and the reported gains are benchmark-specific rather than a guarantee of general self-improvement. I also omitted one analysis paper on intrinsic self-correction because it evaluates the idea rather than introducing a distinct technique. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366?utm_source=openai))"
